04690nam a22007215i 9781477311196DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212016txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016003032  a97814773111967 a10.7560/3103042doi  a(DE-B1597)587369  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aE78.T4bB69 2016 4aE78.T4bB69 2016 7aSOC0030002bisacsh1 aBoyd, Carolyn E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe White Shaman Mural :bAn Enduring Creation Narrative in the Rock Art of the Lower Pecos /cCarolyn E. Boyd. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2016  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Archaic Codices -- tChapter 2. The Painted Landscape -- tChapter 3. Transcribing and Reading Visual Texts -- tChapter 4. A Primer: Abiding Themes in Mesoamerican Thought -- tChapter 5. Pilgrimage to Creation: A Reading of the White Shaman Mural Informed by Huichol Mythology -- tChapter 6. Return to Creation: A Reading of the White Shaman Mural Informed by Nahua Mythology -- tChapter 7. The Art of Transcendence -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe prehistoric hunter-gatherers of the Lower Pecos Canyonlands of Texas and Coahuila, Mexico, created some of the most spectacularly complex, colorful, extensive, and enduring rock art of the ancient world. Perhaps the greatest of these masterpieces is the White Shaman mural, an intricate painting that spans some twenty-six feet in length and thirteen feet in height on the wall of a shallow cave overlooking the Pecos River. In The White Shaman Mural, Carolyn E. Boyd takes us on a journey of discovery as she builds a convincing case that the mural tells a story of the birth of the sun and the beginning of time—making it possibly the oldest pictorial creation narrative in North America. Unlike previous scholars who have viewed Pecos rock art as random and indecipherable, Boyd demonstrates that the White Shaman mural was intentionally composed as a visual narrative, using a graphic vocabulary of images to communicate multiple levels of meaning and function. Drawing on twenty-five years of archaeological research and analysis, as well as insights from ethnohistory and art history, Boyd identifies patterns in the imagery that equate, in stunning detail, to the mythologies of Uto-Aztecan-speaking peoples, including the ancient Aztec and the present-day Huichol. This paradigm-shifting identification of core Mesoamerican beliefs in the Pecos rock art reveals that a shared ideological universe was already firmly established among foragers living in the Lower Pecos region as long as four thousand years ago.  afunded by Cox  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aIndian artzPecos River Valley (N.M. and Tex.) 0aIndian artzPecos River Valley (N.M. and Tex.). 0aIndians of North AmericazPecos River Valley (N.M. and Tex.)xAntiquities. 0aPetroglyphszPecos River Valley (N.M. and Tex.) 0aPetroglyphszPecos River Valley (N.M. and Tex.). 0aRock paintingszPecos River Valley (N.M. and Tex.) 0aRock paintingszPecos River Valley (N.M. and Tex.). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh2 aCoxefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31030440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477311196423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477311196/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK